CNCP v1 23888
{
  "concept": "vuejs/core#12145: defineModel() wrong 'default' type",
  "version": "1.0",
  "created_at": "2026-03-15T04:22:04.719585+00:00",
  "text": "defineModel() wrong 'default' type\n\n### Vue version\n\n3.5.11\n\n### Link to minimal reproduction\n\nhttps://play.vuejs.org/#\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nIn the repro, you can see multiple `defineModel()` macros, none of them throw a type error, even if the types don't match the `Item` interface.\r\n\r\ne.g.:\r\n```ts\r\ninterface Item {\r\n  id: number;\r\n  name: string;\r\n}\r\n\r\ndefineModel<Item>(\"foo1\", {\r\n  default: () => ({ id: 1, name: 123 }), // 'name' should be of type 'string'\r\n})\r\n```\n\n### What is expected?\n\nA type error should be thrown for the `defineModel()` default values.\n\n### What is actually happening?\n\nNo type error is shown.\n\n### System Info\n\n_No response_\n\n### Any additional comments?\n\nIt also behaves kinda strangely with basic types: [playground](https://play.vuejs.org/#)",
  "language": "en",
  "keywords": [
    "scope: types"
  ],
